(812, 1, '2013-04-18 17:16:33', '2013-04-18 22:16:33', 'The purpose of this writing is to propose a capstone project for the Master of Science in Technical Communication degree. My anticipated date of graduation is December 2013.The following outlines my project and how it applies to the course work in the Technical Communication program.\r\n<h2>Introduction</h2>\r\nIn the spring of 2012 I built a website in support of the concert pianist and composer, Fazil Say. I had been following Says career for several months and found it extremely difficult to find information about him written in English. Say is from Turkey and studied music in Germany, and is immensely popular overseas. In the U.S. he is less well known and rarely performs here. I found him very interesting and believe he is enormously talented. I could find no other fan-based website attempting to support his career or discuss his music for an English speaking audience.\r\n\r\nOn June 10, 2012 I launched FazilSayFan.com and began blogging about Say on a daily basis. By this time I had been following his Official Facebook page (even though most of the information was in Turkish) and had downloaded the high resolution press photos available on his website, FazilSay.com, for use on my site. I had a daily Google Alert set up and would write summaries of anything about him that was news related, and I would post YouTube videos and write a few paragraphs about the pieces he was playing and my impressions of the music.\r\n\r\nOn June 15th a friend of mine posted a link to the fansite in the comments on Says Facebook page, and within an hour his PR and Branding colleague, Eren, reached out to me. Eren and I began a casual correspondence for about two months which was very unexpected, but highly enjoyable. Team Say was pleased with my work and really surprised that out of all of Fazils fans, a woman from Minnesota had given up so much time to build a fansite to support him.\r\n\r\nBy July I was Facebook friends with Fazil Say and had limited, but direct contact with him. I mostly communicated with Eren who also managed his Facebook page and was sharing the links to my sites articles to promote what I was writing. I also had many new Turkish Facebook friends by this time, and was connecting with fans from all over the U.S. and the world. It was a very exciting summer for me!\r\n\r\nIn mid August Eren and I spoke for the first time via Google Chat and discussed an informal collaboration. Just two days after our first conversation I woke up to an email from Eren that Says management wanted me to come to Turkey to attend the 13th International Antalya Piano Festival, in Antalya, Turkey, of which Fazil Say is the music director and featured performer. I traveled to Turkey for the festival in November 2012 and met Fazil Say and his team.\r\n\r\nI am proposing the narrative portion of my project be to write more in depth about my collaboration with Team Say, the trip to Turkey, and how each aspect of the Technical Communication program has applied to that collaboration and the fansite itself. The project will also consist of a redesign of FazilSayFan.com that includes sketching, card sorting, prototyping, usability testing, and a WordPress theme built from scratch with custom post types and custom fields. The theme will be constructed using HTML5, CSS3, and the CSS preprocessor Sass, and will also include JavaScript and JQuery.\r\n\r\nIt has been nearly one year since I launched the current fansite and Ive gained a thorough understanding of the nature of Fazil Says compositions and performances. His schedule is fast-paced and he gives concerts several times a month. A fansite to support his career must be highly customized and tailored to suit his calendar of appearances, his many albums, and the non-stop release of his newest compositions. Not to mention the amount that is written about him in the news and online. He is quite famous in Turkey and Europe, and politically active in the free speech issues surrounding Turkey.\r\n\r\nFazil Says fans typically fall into one of three categories: 1) traditional classical music lovers; 2) lovers of his original compositions; and 3) fans that discovered his music through the free speech issues hes encountered in his country. Each of these groups deserves the best user experience possible, and I believe I can deliver that.\r\n<h2>Topics That Will Be Covered In the Narrative</h2>\r\n<h2>Rhetorical Theory</h2>\r\nRhetoric is the best tool I have as a blogger. Fazil Say has a huge repertoire of traditional classical music that he plays in addition to his original compositions. This has been a great opportunity for me to be diverse in my writing and discuss the history of those pieces and their composers, to talk about some of the more technical aspects of music, and his influences related to his original compositions. Using what Ive learned in Rhetorical Theory Ive been able to keep those articles interesting and informative, and most importantly, diverse. Ill give examples of how Ive applied rhetoric to the writing I do for the fansite.\r\n<h2>Research Theory</h2>\r\nResearch Theory taught me the art of annotated bibliographies and the importance of well researched and properly cited writing. I dont want to be a blogger that relies solely on Wikipedia for information, and with the many great books about history and music available, I will start a page on the new site about the books I read and sources I rely on to create an annotated bibliography for readers.\r\n<h2>Document Design</h2>\r\nThe document design class gave me a thorough understanding of Adobe Illustrator and InDesign, and introduced me to WordPress. We learned basic layout, color theory, image resolution principles, typography, and the all-important creative brief; perhaps the single best tool for understanding the needs of a client and how to deliver a website that is tailored for a clients audience. The creative brief helps me articulate what I did and why I did it.\r\n<h2>Technical Communication in an International Context</h2>\r\nThe collaboration with Team Say has been one of the richest and most rewarding experiences Ive ever had. Aside from meeting and spending time with Say, working with his team to deliver content that promotes his career is a lot of fun, but can be very challenging.\r\n\r\nIve found myself facing many of the issues that were discussed in this class related to working in groups across several times zones, and some of the cultural differences that go along with that. I will share those experiences and discuss how I learned (sometimes the hard way) to develop and maintain these relationships.\r\n<h2>Usability Testing for Technical Communication</h2>\r\nThe components of Usability Testing that will be most applicable to my capstone project are sketching, prototyping, card sorting, and usability testing. When I started the fansite I was not prepared for the amount of content I would be creating, and I had never grown and organized something of this size and magnitude. In ten months Ive added a contributing author, posted more than 100 articles, created numerous static pages, and have more than 50 tags. A redesign of the site is as much about aesthetics as it is about user experience and strategic content management.\r\n\r\nI also plan to conduct usability testing to make sure I am creating an exceptional user experience. Ideally that testing will be focused on tasks related to each type of fan Fazil Say has. Those personas will likely be a fan that loves traditional classical music, a fan that mostly enjoys his original compositions, and a fan that discovered Say through his activism in free speech. The tasks will be designed to test how easily each persona can find the information he or she is most interested in, and also whether or not he or she can easily learn about other aspects of Say through the site.\r\n<h2>Advanced Writing and Designing for the Web</h2>\r\nDesigning for the web focused on learning HTML5, CSS and CSS3. This class also introduced me to content strategy, and I did a content inventory and audit of the fan site as my final project for the class, and as the beginning of the capstone project.\r\n<h2>Advanced Editing</h2>\r\nI will take the Advanced Editing class as an independent study concurrently as I work on my Capstone project. This class is important to me because I love to write. I try hard to write rhetorically, but my voice tends to be technical. I love to explain and teach, and find that I can say more with less. I believe a class in advanced editing will not only strengthen basic skills like grammar and punctuation, but will also enable me to be as succinct and concise as possible in my writing.\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nI have thoroughly enjoyed every minute of the Technical Communication program at Metropolitan State University. I never dreamed I would attend graduate school, let alone that I would actually apply my passion to the skills Ive developed, and maybe even someday build a business with these skills to support myself.\r\n\r\nI would also like to argue that much of the content found online today is created by people who are enthusiastic about what they are doing. Maybe they get paid to write or design, or maybe they do it just because they love it, but that content exists because their passion drove them to create it. And when we care deeply enough to spend every waking moment creating great things, thats when we produce our best work. I can think of no better topic than what I have proposed here to complete my course work and graduate from this program.\r\n\r\nThank you.', 'Capstone Proposal', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'capstone-proposal', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=812', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(820, 1, '2013-06-17 18:40:24', '2013-06-18 01:40:24', 'The purpose of this memo is to provide an update on the status of my capstone project for the Master of Science in Technical Communication degree. This update relates to a content inventory and audit of the fan website I built for the concert pianist, Fazil Say.The first part of this task was to create a spreadsheet and begin an inventory of the pages, followed by the posts. A snapshot of the sites content is as follows:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1 Post Type (default)</li>\r\n	<li>1 Category</li>\r\n	<li>17 Pages</li>\r\n	<li>67 Tags</li>\r\n	<li>98 Comments</li>\r\n	<li>119 Articles</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFirst and foremost, this is a WordPress website; therefore the post type is worth noting. Post types are used to create custom post types and taxonomies for customization beyond what traditional categories and tags can offer. Its important to note here that the site only contains one post type (the standard type included in every WordPress installation) but 119 posts, or articles. This inventory and audit will allow me to evaluate the posts so they can be broken down into Custom Post Types for a more customized structure and architecture for the new website.\r\n\r\nThe site makes use of one category, 67 tags, and has 17 pages. The site has received 98 comments, but comments are closed on posts older than 90 days to prevent spam.\r\n\r\nThe website <a href="http://www.usability.gov/how-to-and-tools/methods/content-inventory.html" target="_blank">Usability.gov</a> gives a detailed description of what should be included in a content inventory, and I eventually decided the criteria I would focus on is:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Title</li>\r\n	<li>URL</li>\r\n	<li>Format Type</li>\r\n	<li>Content Type</li>\r\n	<li># of Images</li>\r\n	<li>Author</li>\r\n	<li># of Embedded Videos</li>\r\n	<li>Video URL</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAs the primary content creator of this website, I had an idea of what I would inventory before I started. Soon I discovered that certain pieces of information were more important than others, and that things I thought would be vitally important, like documenting each outbound link, were not nearly as important as I imagined then to be. As an example, I decided that is the pages overall content was relevant to the site, whether or not the pages outbound links were broken would be easier to fix rather than excluding the page altogether. In other words, I prioritized what mattered most if the writing was good and relevant.\r\n\r\nBy then end of the Page inventory I felt like I had a good grasp of this process. I also discovered that the pages architecture in the website was not necessarily in-line with the sites perceived hierarchy. For example, I created a main navigation link called Compositions but used the Orchestral page as the starting point for this series of pages. The Orchestral page being the first in the series, I remember thinking at the time that this was a natural way to lead my audience to these pages. Once on Orchestral, there is a second set of navigation for the remaining pages, all of which represent Fazil Says compositions.\r\n\r\nI understand now that on a sitemap, all of these pages appear to be top level, or parent pages. When in reality, those pages should be assigned as child pages, which is in-line with both the sites hierarchy and architecture.\r\n\r\nNow that the spreadsheet has been created and the pages are inventoried, I will begin the inventory of the sites 119 posts, or articles. I am documenting them as follows:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Title</li>\r\n	<li>URL</li>\r\n	<li>Content Type (More descriptive than the pages)</li>\r\n	<li>Date Posted</li>\r\n	<li>*Relevant</li>\r\n	<li>*Dated Material</li>\r\n	<li>*Poorly Written</li>\r\n	<li>Author</li>\r\n	<li># of Images</li>\r\n	<li># of Videos</li>\r\n	<li>Video URLs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nI will use the Relevant, Dated Material, and Poorly Written as criteria for the audit. These will receive either a yes or noand once completeIll sort the spread sheet and make determinations on what to cut based on the findings.\r\n\r\nI realize there will be many more considerations for inventorying and evaluating this sites content, and I will be open to them as I proceed. But for now, these are the considerations Im working with. After the inventory and audit, Id like to do a card sort and start thinking about how the new wireframe will look. Id also like to perform a handful of usability tests on the current site, using old articles, to get an idea of how usable the current site really is. Im not entirely sure where Ill be with this by July 1<sup>st</sup>, but I do know that the inventory and audit will be complete, and Ill likely write my paper focusing on those two aspects.\r\n\r\nThank you.', 'Project Update Memo', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'project-update-memo', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=820', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(825, 1, '2013-07-01 18:55:07', '2013-07-02 01:55:07', 'The purpose of this paper is to discuss and justify my approach for the content inventory, audit, and information architecture of the website FazilSayFan.com. As I stated in my project proposal, this is a WordPress website I created to support the career of concert pianist and composer, Fazil Say. I launched this site on June 10, 2012 and have created an enormous amount of content that needs to be evaluated and organized before the site can be redesigned.\r\n\r\nNot really knowing where to begin with the project, I was well aware the content on this site needed to be sorted in some way. Using Erin Kissanes The Elements of Content Strategy as a resource, I decided to first inventory, and then audit, the content on a spreadsheet. (Kissane, 2011)\r\n<blockquote> youre going to create an extremely detailed site map that represents every page and other piece of content on the website you are working with, along with every other piece of existing content that may end up on the site, but that currently lives elsewhere.</blockquote>\r\nFor each piece of content, an inventory generally lists a:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>title,</li>\r\n	<li>format (standard text, video, PDF, etc.),</li>\r\n	<li>URL or other location,</li>\r\n	<li>content type (landing page, article, support page, contact page, etc.),</li>\r\n	<li>owner (person responsible for upkeep).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThis first thing I did was a quick snapshot of the content involved:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1 Post Type (default WordPress post type)</li>\r\n	<li>1 Category (Weekly Say)</li>\r\n	<li>17 Pages</li>\r\n	<li>58 Tags</li>\r\n	<li>98 Comments</li>\r\n	<li>119 Posts</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHaving far fewer pages than posts to work with, I began to inventory those first. I started by detailing every bit of information the pages might contain including the URLs for embedded videos and the outbound links. I quickly discovered how tedious and redundant this task was becoming, and reevaluated what I needed to document, and why certain types of information are more or less important.\r\n\r\nI also had the benefit of being this sites content creator, so while there is definitely content here that Ive forgotten about, upon review I immediately recalled writing and publishing it. Kissanes book is geared towards those who will conduct inventories on sites for clients whose content is not familiar. The best example I can give you for this distinction is why I decided not to document the outbound links in any page or post. It seems the best reason to inventory them is to make sure they are still good links. I imagine that if too many links are no longer active, that content may be flagged for deletion or at least a revision.\r\n\r\nI want to know if links are still good or not, but that wont be a determining factor for deletion or revision of the content. This is also is not the only review of content that will take place for the redesign. Because so much content will be revised and reorganized, checking links will be a specific step further along in this process and simply not necessary at this point. In other words, I could think of no reason to document them at this point because I could not image referring to them again on this spreadsheet. If I discover down the road that I am wrong, Ill adjust my process for future inventories.\r\n\r\nWhat I did document are each pages title, URL, format type, content type, number of images, author, number of videos, and video URLs. I was happy to see that each of the video URLs was still active. In my experience, well documented links to videos are important because this content is specific enough that it can be quite difficult to replace it if the original video is no longer available. I also discovered my pages lacked hierarchy. Each page on the site is structured as a top level navigation, but really the pages for the Compositions should be secondary. I also used the Orchestral page in the top level navigation, and relabeled it Compositions; using it as a sort of landing page for all the composition pages. I remember thinking this was a very clever thing to do when I created it last year, but now I see it as very poorly structured; due in part to my lack of understanding of Information Architecture and inability to use the full power of WordPress navigation features.\r\n\r\nAs I started to document the posts, my methodology changed. Instead of content and format type, I made note of a short description. I also noted whether or not a post had comments, and whether or not a post contained outbound links, but not how many or what they are. I also inventoried the video URLs, post URL, and post title just as I did for the pages. The last thing I did was mark the content as Keep, Delete, or Revise. Out of 119 posts, I marked 16 to be deleted because the content was dated and not relevant or useful enough to keep. Of the remaining 103 posts, I was able to determine that 21 posts could be kept but revised or somehow reused. I was also happy to learn that out of 89 embedded videosonly 3 have inactive links that need to be replaced. What remains are 82 posts that I would like to keep, but that I would also like to review once more.\r\n<h2>Summary of Post Inventory and Audit</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Started with 119 Posts\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>16 deleted = 13%</li>\r\n	<li>21 to revise = 17%</li>\r\n	<li>82 remain for further review = 68%</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe final phase of the content inventory and audit was the preliminary Information Architecture for the site. (Please refer to the last pagein the spreadsheet.)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Fazil Say Fan (logo/home)</li>\r\n	<li>Articles (traditional WP post type)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Essays</li>\r\n	<li>Reviews</li>\r\n	<li>Support</li>\r\n	<li>Michaela</li>\r\n	<li>Calendar (custom post type)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Concerts</li>\r\n	<li>Noteworthy Dates</li>\r\n	<li>Events</li>\r\n	<li>Anniversaries</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>News (custom post type)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Informational</li>\r\n	<li>Google Alerts</li>\r\n	<li>Messages from Fazil</li>\r\n	<li>Updates</li>\r\n	<li>Facebook</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Compositions (custom post type)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Orchestral</li>\r\n	<li>Concerto</li>\r\n	<li>Chamber</li>\r\n	<li>Piano</li>\r\n	<li>Song &amp; Oratorio</li>\r\n	<li>Early &amp; Various Works</li>\r\n	<li>Sheet Music</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Images &amp; Videos (could be a page or custom post type, not sure yet)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Official Photos</li>\r\n	<li>Official Videos</li>\r\n	<li>Fan Photos</li>\r\n	<li>Fan Videos</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>About &amp; Biography (page)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Fazil</li>\r\n	<li>Angela</li>\r\n	<li>Michaela</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Recordings (custom post type, no categories)</li>\r\n	<li>Additional Navigation &amp; Functionality\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Breadcrumbs</li>\r\n	<li>Tag Cloud</li>\r\n	<li>Search</li>\r\n	<li>Subscribe</li>\r\n	<li>Contact</li>\r\n	<li>Social\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Facebook</li>\r\n	<li>Twitter</li>\r\n	<li>Pinterest</li>\r\n	<li>YouTube</li>\r\n	<li>RSS</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Footer\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Disclosure</li>\r\n	<li>Privacy Policy</li>\r\n	<li>Copyright</li>\r\n	<li>Links</li>\r\n	<li>Site map</li>\r\n	<li>Archive page</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>A snapshot of the new Information Architecture</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>5 Post Types</li>\r\n	<li>Approximately 20 New Categories</li>\r\n	<li>Many pages will be turned into posts.</li>\r\n	<li>The majority of pages will contain static information like the disclosure, privacy policy, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>Tags and comments will not change.</li>\r\n	<li>Tags will not be custom taxonomies but will be universal for all post types.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nThis project has given me a lot of confidence to move forward with the redesign of FazilSayFan.com. Ive done very little over the last six months to keep this site up to date, mostly because it is so difficult to manage the content. One thing I learned as I conducted this inventory was some of the great content Ive created that is buried and not being seen. It also forced me to look back at the truly awful writing I published in the early days of the site. This was my first blog and I had to produce a staggering amount of bad content before I found my voice and discovered what I wanted to communicate to the world about Fazil Say. Admittedly, I do not have time to write the lengthy articles I once wrote, but that doesnt mean this fan site cant still be an excellent source of information with timely updates about Fazil Say.\r\n\r\nThe next step in this project will be a second review of the content Id like to keep, assigning that content appropriately based on the preliminary information architecture, and then a wireframe of the new site.\r\n<h2>Resources for this project:</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>"Content inventory - Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia."<cite>Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</cite>. N.p., n.d. Web. 1 July 2013. &lt;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Content_inventory&gt;.</li>\r\n	<li>Kissane, Erin.<cite>The Elements of Content Strategy.</cite> New York: A Book Apart, 2011. Print.</li>\r\n	<li>"Methods | Usability.gov."<cite>Home | Usability.gov</cite>. N.p., n.d. Web. 1 July 2013. &lt;http://www.usability.gov/methods/design_site/inventory.html&gt;.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Results of Content Inventory', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'results-of-content-inventory-and-audit-for-fazilsayfan', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=825', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1015, 1, '2013-12-01 16:50:08', '2013-12-02 00:50:08', 'I started learning about web design in 2010 when I took a Dreamweaver class at the local community college. I had been trying to figure out Dreamweaver for months, but I was thoroughly confused by HTML and CSS, and no online tutorial seemed to be simple enough for me to get it. I needed help. I needed a person, not a tutorial or a book, to ask questions and get feedback. I learned more about Dreamweaver in that evening than in the previous three months, and over the next couple of days I built my first website.\r\n\r\nI didnt start learning WordPress until early 2012. I knew what a content management system was, but I had to be convinced they were better than static websites. Eighteen months later Im designing and building WordPress themes for my clients, and I find myself in the unique position of being asked for help by WordPress newcomers. In fact, in the last week Ive been contacted by several people asking if I could answer questions related to WordPress and web design. These requests inspired me to write a blog post outlining what I think is important, as well as the resources I use to be a better designer and business owner.\r\n\r\n<em>*All links referenced throughout are at the end of the article.</em>\r\n<h2>Hardware</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Computer: Dell Inspiron One with 23 inch touch monitor running Windows 8</li>\r\n	<li>Printer: Epson Artisan 725</li>\r\n	<li>Printer: HP Deskjet 1000</li>\r\n	<li>Microphone: MXL 900 USB</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe Dell Inspiron has a built in web cam that is quite nice, but does not have a built in microphone. I leave my MXL 990 plugged in at all times for online chats and to record screencasts. I use the keyboard that came with the computer, and I use a Microsoft wireless mouse.\r\n<h2>Software &amp; Apps</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Text Editor: Sublime Text 2</li>\r\n	<li>CSS &amp; Javascript Preprocessor: Prepros</li>\r\n	<li>FTP: Filezilla &amp; Expandrive</li>\r\n	<li>Graphics &amp; Image Editors: Adobe Photoshop, Illustrator, and InDesign</li>\r\n	<li>iOS Simulator: Microsoft Webmatrix</li>\r\n	<li>Screencasts: Snagit 11</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Sublime Text</h3>\r\nThese are the software applications I use almost every day to design and develop web sites and record tutorials for my clients. Sublime Text is the best text editor Ive used, and it is my most used piece of software. A license costs $70.00 USD, but you can download a free trial and use it before you buy it. Trust me, its worth every penny.\r\n<h3>Prepros</h3>\r\nI started writing CSS in Sass/SCSS earlier this summer, and I use Prepros to compile and process all of my style sheets and Javascript files. If you arent familiar with this, I highly recommend you start learning to write in Sass or LESS and preprocess your CSS. Its not drastically different from writing vanilla CSS, but it is a much better, more extensible language, and your style sheets will be far more organized. Prepros is free, open source software for both Mac and Windows, and it includes full Compass support.\r\n\r\nEverything about preprocessing is awesome, and you should jump in and start learning to do it as soon as possible. Ill include resources at the end of this article on how you can get started with Sass (or LESS), and the apps available to use them.\r\n<h3>Filezilla &amp; Expandrive</h3>\r\nI use Filezilla to upload files via FTP, and I use Expandrive to connect to a live server and edit files. Filezilla is free, open source software, but Expandrive costs $40.00 USD after a 30 day free trial. Using FTP, however, is quickly becoming frowned upon in the design and development community in favor of version control. This is something Im just starting to learn about and implement in my personal projects. Chris Coyiers screencast called Lets Suck at Github Together on CSS-Tricks is an excellent way to get started learning about version control, and I plan to use Github for all of my client work and personal projects by the end of 2013.\r\n<h3>Photoshop</h3>\r\nOf all Adobes products, I use Photoshop more than anything. Most of my design starts in Ps with basic design comps, and its in your best interest to learn the Ps features specific to web design for this reason. Theres been a lot of hot drama recently over designing in the browser versus designing in Photoshop. In my workflow, all design starts in Ps, and once approved by the client, I move it to the browser. Every one of us has to determine the workflow that best suits the client and the job, and this works for me on most projects.\r\n\r\nMy attitude about Photoshop comps is to treat them as mood boards for color, typography, assets, and basic layout. I dont have time to code a design in the browser as a comp for clients. Photoshop makes this process faster and easier; and the better your Ps and CSS skills become, the better at designing comps youll be.\r\n<h3>Webmatrix (iOS Simulator)</h3>\r\nMicrosoft Webmatrix is free to download, and I use it for the iOS simulator. There are lots of ways to resize your browser window to see how your responsive designs behave, but an iOS simulator is both a smaller view and your sites behavior on iOS for iPhone and iPad.\r\n<h3>Snagit</h3>\r\nSnagit is screen capture and recording software from Tech Smith. Theres a free 30 day trial, then a license will cost you about $50.00 USD. I record a lot of screencasts, from tutorials to usability tests, to private videos for clients and friends. I probably record something for someone at least three or four times a week, so this is a great tool for me. Tech Smith also has a free app called Jing to record short, five minute screencasts, or a more expensive option called Camtasia Studio for about $300.00 USD that includes video editing. In addition to screen recording, Snagit takes full screen captures which can be very handy.\r\n<h2>Skills</h2>\r\n<h3>Usability &amp; User Experience (UX)</h3>\r\nThese are the things, that in my opinion, you must understand to be a web designer. Design isnt just about knowing HTML and CSS, or being good at Photoshop; its also about designing a website that is usable. You must have an understanding of usability and creating good user experiences (UX) to be an effective designer. I was very lucky to take a graduate level usability course when I worked on my masters degree, because I guarantee that without the class, it would have taken me years to understand how important usability is. The best thing you can do for yourself and your clients is read Steve Krugs Dont Make Me Think to learn more about this important, and sometimes overlooked, aspect of web design.\r\n<h3>Content Strategy</h3>\r\nYou should develop an understanding of content strategy and working with content on the web. WordPress is, after all, a content management system, and web sites are above all else, words.\r\n\r\nPeople visit websites for information, and if content isnt organized and well written, your job will be very difficult. Because how exactly do you design a web site without content? How do you determine layout, taxonomy, or any kind of structure without knowing what kind of content will be on the site? Plan to spend a tremendous amount of time educating your clients about content, and interviewing them to understand their business and their audience. You need to understand who will visit the website and what information theyll be looking for. If your client cant answer those questions, consider whether the job is right for you, and how effective your work will be without this information.\r\n<h3>HTML5</h3>\r\nYou must be very good at HTML5 and CSS. There is no way around this, because these two things are the framework for every web site. Dreamweaver is a wonderful tool, but if you cant look at a Ps comp and at least write the HTML to match what you see, you need to stop what youre doing and learn this skill. There is no shame in keeping your favorite HTML/CSS book at your side or on your lap as you work, but you must not rely on an HTML template from Dreamweaver as the backbone of every website you design. If it helps you get started because it includes all the great stuff you typically find in the &lt;head&gt;, thats fine. But really, you should know what all of those things are and why theyre there anyway. And you dont need Dreamweaver to get that information. I think youre much better off using HTML5 Boilerplate as the starting point for any project.\r\n\r\nHTML5 is a gorgeously semantic markup language. Its rich and provides so much meaning to content that when used properly, it will make your websites accessible and SEO friendly. Learn to write excellent HTML5. Understand when to use a &lt;section&gt; tag and when to use a &lt;div&gt;. Do not skimp on this because it is one of the most important skills you can have.\r\n<h3>CSS</h3>\r\nCSS is design. At the end of the day, CSS determines the look of your website in its entirety. We use CSS for layout, color, images, and behavior. I struggled with CSS for much longer than I care to admit, but I have finally reached a point in my personal development where I can write CSS with confidenceor at least without being terrified. That doesnt mean Im an expert or that I never have to Google how to achieve something using CSS, it just means that I am finally comfortable writing CSS to make my designs happen. The more I learn about CSS, the better I become as a designer. If youre new to web design, plan to spend a long timemaybe even yearsunderstanding CSS. Youll probably never learn everything, but a very good foundation will be one of your greatest assets.\r\n<h3>Responsive Design</h3>\r\nCSS includes knowing responsive design, which at its core, is CSS applied to your designs when the browser is resized, or the site is being viewed on a device that is not a traditional computer. Learn everything you can about making your designs responsive, and what it means to design mobile first, if thats appropriate for your clients audience. If nothing else, understand that Google is paying attention to web sites that are (or arent) optimized for smartphone and tablet users, and be prepared to explain to your clients why you are (or arent) designing responsive web sites.\r\n\r\nNow that Ive started designing my sites responsively, its no longer a question of whether or not the client wants to me pay me for responsive web design. Its included in my price because thats how I design. Period. There are sites in my portfolio that arent responsive because I made them or used a WordPress theme that was not responsive before I learned how to do it. Moving forward theyll be replaced with mobile ready, responsive web sites.\r\n<h3>Learn about basic design concepts and principles</h3>\r\nJohn McWade was the first person to start desktop publishing IN THE WORLD. He is one of the best graphic designersEVERand his series of design books and guides from Before &amp; After Magazine are the best out there. McWade doesnt teach illustration or how to use software, he teaches layout, color, and typography. His principles will help you better understand white space, choosing fonts, and applying color pallets to your web designs. There are conventions we follow as web designers that are specific to usability and user experience, but we still have a tremendous amount of freedom to make our designs unique and creative, and learning about basic design techniques is as important as learning HTML and CSS.\r\n<h2>Resources</h2>\r\n<h3>Books</h3>\r\nI own more web design books than I can possibly list here, but these are my favorites.\r\n\r\nThe Smashing Magazine\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>LibraryExcellent books from a great website, smashingmagainze.com</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nA Book Apart Library\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A series of books that evolved from alistapart.com. I cant recommend these enough. They are wonderfully engaging and perfect for all skills levels, especially beginners.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nDigging into WordPress\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Fantastic book about WordPress by Jeff Starr and Chris Coyier</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe Tao of WordPress\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Another terrific book about WordPress by Jeff Starr</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMurachs HTML5 and CSS3\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>One of the best books you can own to learn HTML5 and CSS/CSS3. If you have any book at your side while you work, this should be the one.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBefore &amp; After Magazine: How to design cool stuff\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Both the books and subscription to the magazine are excellent resources for designers. McWade will get you thinking about typography, layout, and color in easy to follow tutorials.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Websites</h3>\r\nCSS-Tricks.com\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Chris Coyier is the creator of CSS-Tricks and his blog and screencasts have taught me more about web design than anything else. A subscription to The Lodge is well worth the $19.99 USD per month to watch his v10 redesign and mobile first design series. Youll see him in think critically and run into the same problems we all have as web designers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTutsplus.com\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Tuts Plus runs a series of websites that covers everything from WordPress, Photoshop, Illustration, Development, and much, much more.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLynda.com\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Lynda is subscription based online tutorials from industry leaders in design and development. Over the last couple of years theyve expanded to include videos on running a business to dealing with difficult people. Chris Coyier of CSS-Tricks recorded a tutorial about workflow and WordPress, and it is one of the best tutorials Ive seen if you want to build your own WordPress themes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTympanus.net/codrops (Codrops)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Codrops is a playground for innovative design techniques centered around CSS and Javascript. Theyre creative and fun and always include a demo and the source files. Theyre also really good at gathering the webs latest news and resources and combining them into a weekly resource called the Collective.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCodex.wordpress.org (WordPress Codex)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>If you want to design and develop websites using WordPress, you will spend hours reading the WordPress Codex. Everything you want to know about WordPress is in the Codex, and you should read it early and often.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Podcasts</h3>\r\nThe webs best workers are also podcasting. These are the podcasts I listen to to stay up to date on web standards, best practices, tips for running my business and technology in general.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Shop Talk Show</li>\r\n	<li>Boag World</li>\r\n	<li>BizCraft</li>\r\n	<li>The Tech Guy</li>\r\n	<li>Hello Monday</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\nAre you overwhelmed yet? Thats okay! This is a lot of information. But quite frankly, most of this I only figured out in the last year, all while working full time and going graduate school. If I can do it, so can you.\r\n\r\nI could go on and on about what new web designers should learn to be better at building web sites, but these are just the things that work for me. Im still a relatively new designer, or at least thats how I see myself, and Im learning new things every day; forming processes to suit my needs and my clients. Part of this journey will be for you to open your mind and your heart to the opportunities and people that will come into your life to help you learn and grow. Engage with fellow designers, be creative, and above all else, if you want to be good at building websites, then you should JUST BUILD WEBSITES. Build as many as you can, as often as you can, and youll be good at it sooner than you think.\r\n<h3>Links</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href="http://tympanus.net/codrops/">http://tympanus.net/codrops/</a>- Codrops</li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://tutsplus.com/">https://tutsplus.com/</a>- Tuts Plus</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.bamagazine.com/Default.asp">http://www.bamagazine.com/Default.asp</a>- Before &amp; After Magazine</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2013/06/changes-in-rankings-of-smartphone_11.html">http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.com/2013/06/changes-in-rankings-of- smartphone_11.html</a>- Google &amp; Responsive Design/SEO</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.techsmith.com/">http://www.techsmith.com/</a>- Tech Smith/Snagit</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://css-tricks.com/video-screencasts/101-lets-suck-at-github-together/">http://css-tricks.com/video-screencasts/101-lets-suck-at-github-together/</a>- Let''s Suck at Github Together</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://css-tricks.com/">http://css-tricks.com/</a>- CSS-Tricks</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.expandrive.com/expandrive">http://www.expandrive.com/expandrive</a>- Expandrive</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://alphapixels.com/prepros/">http://alphapixels.com/prepros/</a>- Prepos</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.sublimetext.com/">http://www.sublimetext.com/</a>- Sublime Text</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.amazon.com/HP-2009M-20-Inch-LCD-Monitor/dp/B001UHOX2S">http://www.amazon.com/HP-2009M-20-Inch-LCD-Monitor/dp/B001UHOX2S</a>- HP Monitor</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://www.dell.com/us/p/inspiron-one-23-2330-aio/pd">http://www.dell.com/us/p/inspiron-one-23-2330-aio/pd</a>- Dell Inspiron</li>\r\n</ul>', 'How I Work', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-i-work', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1015', 0, 'post', '', 0),
