(1110, 1, '2014-01-16 11:57:05', '2014-01-16 17:57:05', '<h2>Introduction, Content Inventory, and Audit</h2>\r\n<h3>Introduction</h3>\r\nDuring the summer of 2012 I created a website in support of the concert pianist and composer, Fazil Say. I had been following Says career for about six months, and it was difficult to find information about him in English. Say is from Turkey and studied music in Germany, and most of what is published about him is in another language. I found him very interesting, and I believe he is enormously talented, and there were no other fan-based websites attempting to support his career or discuss his music for an English speaking audience.\r\n\r\nMy project proposal was to redesign the website I launched 18 months ago. In the time since the site has been created, a lot of content has been written and the site was very unorganized. I wanted the new website to be both attractive and usable, and it needed a comprehensive inventory and audit before any design could begin. The site also needed a full round of usability testing. I had a good idea of what needed to change, but I also knew that usability testing and user feedback would flush out any remaining issues that should be addressed.\r\n<h3>Content Inventory &amp; Audit</h3>\r\nA snapshot of the site before the content inventory and audit is as follows: 119 posts, 98 comments, and 58 tags. There was one category being used with WordPresss default post type, and there were 17 pages of static content. This is an extraordinary amount of content, and every bit of it needed to be evaluated to be sure it was still relevant and timely. The content also needed to be evaluated as something that is either static or dynamic.\r\n\r\nGenerally speaking, all content in a content management system is dynamic. WordPress uses a programming language called PHP to dynamically retrieve content from a database, and it makes no difference if that content is a post, a page, an image, or a link. However, when used in the context of a discussion about posts and pages, the term dynamic refers to the type of content that is appropriate for a post, versus a page.\r\n\r\nCertain parts of a WordPress website are syndicated via an RSS Feed, and the content published in WordPresss default post type is included in that feed. This is important if a website has an audience who subscribes to the content being published. If content is published to pages, it doesnt appear in an RSS feed. If content is published in a blog, or as a post, this is the content that is syndicated.\r\n\r\nWhen I started the fansite, I understood this concept at its root. But I also recalled how quickly I created content, and knew the lines had been blurred as I struggled to make everything fit into a site that had no customization. And as I suspected, I found a lot of content that could be moved to more customized sections of the site.\r\n\r\nThe inventory consisted of a large spreadsheet where each page and post was inventoried, and as I did so, I made notes of what I wanted to keep or change, and how that content might be reorganized in the new site. Included in the inventory was each page or post title, URL, the author, whether or not it contained images, embedded YouTube or Vimeo videos, the date it was published, and whether there were any comments. Any page or post with links and videos had to be checked for dead links. Interestingly, of the 89 embedded videos, only three videos were no longer available and needed replacements.\r\n\r\nUpon completion of the inventory, I had an enormous spreadsheet of data and a very good idea of how to proceed with my project. I had content that could fit into the following classifications:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Traditional Posts</li>\r\n	<li>Traditional Pages</li>\r\n	<li>Calendar of Events</li>\r\n	<li>Compositions</li>\r\n	<li>Images &amp; Videos</li>\r\n	<li>Records &amp; Albums</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nA default installation of WordPress includes traditional posts and pages, but the remaining sections of the site would be created using custom post types.\r\n\r\nCustom post types are what make WordPress such a powerful and highly customizable content management system. By default, custom post types are not included in a sites RSS feed. For this reason, any WordPress website posting to a blog should always use the default post type.\r\n\r\nCustom post types are a way to design sections of a website for specific kinds of content. In my case, I knew I needed to make an event calendar, so I created a custom post type where each entry would be an entry onto the calendar. I also knew that I wanted to make a video galley, where each video posted with a title and link would appear in a gallery of videos. Understanding how to create and use custom post types was the single most important aspect to moving forward with this sites redesign. After a full year of creating content, I was armed with a very good understanding of the work being done by Fazil Say, and how I wanted to deliver that information to my audience.\r\n\r\nIn addition to custom post types, we can create custom taxonomies. On the old site I used one category and 58 tags in my default post type. In WordPress, taxonomies with hierarchy are categories, and taxonomies without hierarchy are tags. There are some unwritten guidelines about how content is organized using taxonomies. The best analogy is to think of categories like they are chapters in a book, and tags like the books index. Chapters in a book do not have duplicate content, and nor should your posts appear in multiple categories. In a books index, however, content can be duplicated throughout, and your posts can have several duplicate tags.\r\n\r\nUsing custom post types we can also create custom taxonomies that are specific to just that post type, with or without hierarchy, and we can call them anything we want. Where the default post type calls them categories and tags, I can create a custom taxonomy without hierarchy for my custom post type videos, but instead I call them keywords. They function just like a tag, but they only apply to the videos; nowhere else.\r\n\r\nThis is an incredibly powerful way to organize content, and one that cannot be fully realized without thorough knowledge of a sites content and audience.', 'Reflection Paper: Part One', 'During the summer of 2012 I created a website in support of the concert pianist and composer, Fazil Say. I had been following Says career for about six months, and it was difficult to find information about him in English...', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-part-one', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1110', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1112, 1, '2014-07-14 19:47:18', '2014-07-15 02:47:18', '<h2>Usability Testing - Old Site</h2>\r\nWhen I completed the content inventory and audit, I did a round of usability testing to get feedback on the current version of the website. I was confident I knew what needed to change, but I wanted to see for myself how people use the site, and make sure I understand how a typical user looks for information about Fazil Say.\r\n\r\nFirst, I wrote a short usability test with four tasks and six post test questions. I selected five participants and recorded each test. I explained the purpose of the test, and I asked each person to think out loud as they completed the tasks. My participants were Deb, a graphic designer and artist from California, Ed, a web developer from Romania, Eren, a member of Team Say in Istanbul, Cheryl, a Facebook friend and Fazil Say fan from North Carolina, and Gulay, another Facebook friend and a childhood friend of Fazil Say living in the U.K. Each test was conducted via Google Hangout or Skype, and recorded with screen capture software. For the complete test, and a list of links to view the recorded tests, please refer to the last page in this document.\r\n\r\nThe most notable result of the testing was an absence of a way to search the site. This was something that I was aware of, and I was planning to build a search function on the new site, but I did not realize how important it was until almost every single person wanted to use the search at some point in the test. Some participants only find information on a website using search, forgoing any kind of navigation that is available. This was a surprise to me, because I tend to use the search function after several attempts to find information fails.\r\n\r\nI was also surprised to find that a task related to using tags to find articles related to one topic could not be completed by all of the participants. Tags are an important part of my site, and I included them believing that search would be less important if tags were available. What I learned is that, while tags are important, people dont necessarily know what they are or how they function.\r\n\r\nThe third surprise was related to a task about finding information about the websites creator, me. The site had a static about page with a short narrative about myself, but there was no picture of me, and nobody actually read the narrative, so even if they navigated to the about page, they did not realize this was a page about me. I think this speaks volumes about how people consume content on the internet. Should content continue to be written with great care if nobody really reads it? Yes, but it should be concise and written with brevity. The care, then, is to make sure that content still has the warmth of my message.', 'Reflection Paper: Part Two', 'When I completed the content inventory and audit, I did a round of usability testing to get feedback on the current version of the website. I was confident I knew what needed to change, but I wanted to see for myself how people use the site...', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-usability-testing-old-site', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1112', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1114, 1, '2014-07-16 12:00:47', '2014-07-16 19:00:47', '<h2>Static Design</h2>\r\nAt this point, I was finally ready to make some design decisions about the new site. A typical web design workflow is to start designing in Photoshop, and then move that design to the browser with HTML5 and CSS. And finally, replace static HTML5 content with PHP and dynamically retrieve content from the database. There is a push in modern web design, however, to do more design in the browser and less design in Photoshop. As websites become responsive and adaptable to an unlimited number of screen sizes and mobile devices, its becoming difficult to design in a fixed environment like Photoshop.\r\n\r\nAs a new web designer, Im still developing my workflow and I know that my Photoshop skills are not as strong as my development and coding skills. I was having trouble envisioning how different aspects of the site would look and behave with Photoshop, so I decided to take a different approach, and rather than try to make every big design decision from the outset, I focused on just one aspect of the sites layout and proceeded from there.\r\n\r\nWhen designing for WordPress, there are additional challenges and things to keep in mind in the early stages of a design. First, there is HTML5 which is the skeleton of a website, and the programming language that gives content its semantic value. WordPress functions, written in PHP, also generate HTML5 so content can be structured and styled. So when I know that I want to insert a tag cloud in my sidebar, I need to check the WordPress documentation to see exactly how their HTML5 will be generated when the static design is converted to WordPress. This allows me to create static HTML5 that I know matches perfectly for a seamless transition.\r\n\r\nNext, WordPress inserts class names into many of its functions, and class names are used in CSS to apply styles to HTML5. Knowing ahead of time what those class names are, and where theyre inserted into the code is tremendously helpful and can save hours of work. Understanding these two characteristics of WordPress are really important, but because I had never designed a site so large and with so many customizations, it also slowed me down. Each time I was ready to write HTML5 and CSS to build a new part of the site, I had to stop and make sure that it could be done in WordPress, and if so, how WordPress would handle it. This made the design phase of the project, by far, the longest, taking a full two months. But on the other hand, it was an incredible learning experience and Ive gained valuable knowledge that I will use many times in future projects.\r\n\r\nWith that being said, the first part of the site I decided to design was the video gallery. I decided not to worry about color or typography, but to concentrate on the HTML5 and CSS, and how to layout the videos on the screen and how they would behave at different screen sizes. In 24 hours I designed the structure and functionality for my video gallery, and that was all it took to get me started. After the video gallery was in place, I designed one section at a time, starting with the home page. This is where I made my major aesthetic design decisions about color and typography, and I continued on that path until much of the design was complete.\r\n<h2>Version Control &amp; Collaboration</h2>\r\nAfter about 75% of the static site was designed and built, I wanted to start keeping track of my work using the version control software, Git. Git is an open source project for distributed version control. It installs locally, and each time changes are committed, they are stored as a version of the project making it easy to roll back to previous versions if necessary.\r\n\r\nAfter Git is installed in a local environment, and a repository is created for the project, an exact copy of the repository is set up in the cloud. This repository, or repo, acts as an intermediary between the local environment and the server. As soon as a local commit is made, it gets pushed to the repository online, and those changes get deployed to the server.\r\n\r\nGit is especially helpful when working it teams. With distributed teams of developers and designers, code can be easily reviewed and merged with Git. And this is the reason I decided to start learning Git. I have been working closely with a developer in Romania named Ed Ungureanu for more than a year who assisted me with parts of the site. I wanted to make sure we werent over-writing each others work, and make it easy to roll back to previous versions of the site if necessary. Also, when Ed makes changes, I want pull those changes from the online repository and merge them with my local copy of the site. Then I can go line by line through the code and review the work being done.\r\n\r\nGit, it turns out, has a very steep learning curve. Ed and I had never used it before, but we both wanted to learn it. We spent almost a full week getting the software installed and configured, and working out a system for how changes would be reviewed and deployed. The biggest obstacle was that I use a PC and Ed uses a Mac, and we each use different software with a different GUI making it extremely difficult to communicate about our Git workflows. Eventually we developed a system that worked for us, and I became the final authority on everything that was deployed to the live site. We both had full access to the repository, but if any code conflicted, I made the final decision.', 'Reflection Paper: Part Three', 'At this point, I was finally ready to make some design decisions about the new site. A typical web design workflow is to start designing in Photoshop, and then move that design to the browser with HTML5 and CSS', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-static-design-version-control-collaboration', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1114', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1116, 1, '2014-07-18 12:00:40', '2014-07-18 19:00:40', '<h2>Moving to WordPress</h2>\r\nOnce we got version control set up, I still had two sections of the site to design: compositions and the image gallery. But at this point I was very anxious to start turning my design into a WordPress theme. With version control set up to track our changes, I decided to get started writing the code to build the WordPress theme.\r\n\r\nFirst, I pulled the old sites content from the servers database to start a new database in my local environment. Then, I started writing PHP and custom query loops. The home page alone has four custom queries to dynamically pull content from the database, and it was awesome to see the content I created come together with my custom design.\r\n\r\nThis is also where I started to need some help from Ed. I spent hours reading the WordPress documentation to learn most of what went into this site, but there were a few things I could never quite get a handle on that I decided to build anyway. Ed is very experienced with WordPress and assured me there wasnt anything he hasnt been able to accomplish with this platform.\r\n\r\nTo be specific, I needed help with the main archive page where I wanted one heading for each set of articles published in a month. When a loop retrieves content, it loops through each piece of HTML5 once, and generates one of each kind of content. So, if there are six articles published in October, there will be six headers and six articles; not one header and six articles. Ed wrote a custom loop using a function called $wpdb that interfaces with the database to pull content from any table and insert it anywhere. This kind of function is extremely complex, but my design could not be accomplished any other way. Ed also helped me paginate the video gallery archive view, and the single post view of the albums. Pagination in the default post type is very easy to accomplish, but in custom post types there is added complexity because WordPress, by default, doesnt understand the uniqueness of custom post types. Therefore, Ed wrote a special loop just to tell WordPress which posts to paginate. These three things, plus his assistance with version control, were his contributions to the project.\r\n<h2>Feedback from Fazil Say  October 5, 2013</h2>\r\nJust as I was moving the site to WordPress I sent a link to the static version of the design to Team Say in Istanbul. They were very pleased with what I was doing, and within a few days I received a message from Fazil Say:\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<blockquote>i will write on turkish a paragraph about your new website... thank u sooo much Angela u are a real angel</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nFazil and I are Facebook friends, but outside of that, I do not have any direct contact with him. I was roughly half way done with the redesign, and while I was very happy with my progress, I was also a little bit tired and thinking a lot about how much work I still had to do. His messagethose few wordsgave me a huge boost and made me feel so good that he appreciated my effort.', 'Reflection Paper: Part Four', 'Once we got version control set up, I still had two sections of the site to design: compositions and the image gallery. But at this point I was very anxious to start turning my design into a WordPress theme', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-moving-wordpress-feedback-fazil-say', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1116', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1118, 1, '2014-07-20 12:00:07', '2014-07-20 19:00:07', '<h2>Launching the Site</h2>\r\nMy goal was to launch the site on October 31, 2013. It was important to me the site go live and I start getting feedback from my audience at least a full month before the project was due to be turned in. I finished building the theme by the middle of October, and I spent two and a half weeks just working with content. I was very happy I built this time for content into the project, because as I arranged and organized content, there were areas of the site that had to be modified, and I had plenty of time to make necessary adjustments. I also had time to review and edit each post.\r\n\r\nLate in the evening on October 31st, I launched the site. In my mind, it was only 95% ready, but I decided that I still had the next 30 days to make changes, get feedback, conduct a second round of usability testing, and write the reflection paper. After it went live, I posted updates on Facebook about the new site, I and went to bed. The next morning when I woke up, Team Say had shared the link on their Facebook page and the site received some very good traffic overnight. The feedback from other fans on Facebook was positive, and I was quite pleased.\r\n<h2>More Feedback from Fazil Say  November 3, 2013</h2>\r\nAt this point, I stopped working for several days to take care of some personal business. Fazil had been on a short tour in Japan and was just returning to Istanbul for more performances. Soon I received another message from him:\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<blockquote>fantastic Angela fantastic... i will contact eren</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\nThat was followed by a message from a member of Fazils management, Eren Yagmuroglu, that Fazil really did love the site, and they would be in touch shortly with an article for me to publish.', 'Reflection Paper: Part Five', 'My goal was to launch the site on October 31, 2013. It was important to me the site go live and I start getting feedback from my audience at least a full month before the project was due to be...', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-launching-site-feedback-fazil-say', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1118', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1121, 1, '2014-07-22 12:00:17', '2014-07-22 19:00:17', '<h2>Usability Testing - New Site</h2>\r\nTwo weeks after the launch, I began a second round of usability testing. I decided to use the same tasks for this round as I did for the first, and to compare those results. Of the five participants from the first round, only two were available for testing this time: Deb from California, and Cheryl from North Carolina. The three new participants were Babak, a graphic designer and Turkish-English translator from Azerbaijan, Donna, a legal assistant from Minnesota, and Melissa, a certified nursing assistant from Minnesota.\r\n\r\nIn this round of testing, much to my dismay, search continued to be an issue. For aesthetic value, I put the search box at the bottom of the page in the footer, not an uncommon place to do so, yet nearly every participant commented that it should be at the top of the page near the navigation.\r\n\r\nAside from this, the participants completed all of the tasks without difficulty except for the task related to finding all articles about just one topic. Again, I hoped people would find a very prominent tag cloud in the sidebar, but the sidebar is only visible when visiting an article related section of the site. I used the term archives in the navigation to indicate this was an archive of all the articles written, but only one participant knew what that meant. The task, specifically, was to find every article about a particular composition, so most participants clicked on the menu item compositions to complete the task. This was an indicator of two things: first, that I should include links to articles related to compositions in the compositions section of the site, and to change the navigation from archives to articles.\r\n\r\nIn general, I received user feedback about how surprising the improvements were. When I told people I was planning to redesign the site, I received many comments about how it should not be changed, or how it could not possibly be better than it was. I think that was a reaction to the old sites visual appeal, because the more I learned about WordPress leading up to the redesign, the more displeased I was with the old sites functionality. While I didnt dislike the old sites color and typography, I did want to create an original design, but my focus was on the sites structure and functionality.', 'Reflection Paper: Part Six', 'Two weeks after the launch, I began a second round of usability testing. I decided to use the same tasks for this round as I did for the first, and to compare those results. Of the five participants from the...', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-usability-testing-new-site', '', '', '2014-10-22 10:05:07', '2014-10-22 17:05:07', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1121', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1123, 1, '2014-07-24 12:00:35', '2014-07-24 19:00:35', 'The best part about this project is that it is personal, but not just because I love Fazil Says music. This is the type of work I want to do for a living, and I am passionate about doing it really well. I also went into this project knowing that when the redesign was complete, the real work to maintain it and continue creating content was just beginning. I have a place to try new techniques for layout, design, and content strategy with a diverse audience to give me feedback.\r\n\r\nWith the exception of one class in the technical communication program, I am a self-taught web designer. Ive been building websites for about four years, but I never really did it well. Ive struggled to learn HTML and CSS, and the websites I built prior to this year reflected my lack of confidence and understanding of some basic concepts.\r\n\r\nOnce I entered the technical communication program, my eyes were immediately opened to new ideas and technologies. The biggest of those was my introduction to WordPress by Fred Carpenter in the Document Design class. That set me down a path of customizing WordPress themes for 18 months, and making many, many websites and working with lots of content. Eventually I started to understand how content should be written and organized, and then how to make sure a website is usable.\r\n\r\nEvery class in this program has contributed my development as a web designer, from a thorough knowledge of rhetoric and the power of language, to research theory and writing and becoming a critical researcher and content provider. But the two classes that catapulted my web design career were Usability Testing and Writing and Designing for the Web. I had been reading a lot about usability, but I didnt understand its roll in web design or how significant it is. Creating personas, writing and conducting usability tests, and analyzing their results were an eye opening experience. It seems quite simple now, but I finally understood that websites are built for the people who use them, not for the designers who build them.\r\n\r\nDespite how much I already knew about web design and WordPress, I was not moving forward as a designer. I had stalled because I lacked a foundation in HTML and CSS, and I had become very impatient trying to learn the basics of these programming languages. But when I purchased the books required for the class, I immediately sat down and read the first four chapters of the textbook titled Murachs HTML5 &amp; CSS3. In the first 100 pages of that book, I learned things about HTML and CSS that I had been struggling to understand for several years. I have purchased many books on these topics, and this book is, by far, the easiest to read and understand about web design. Throughout this class we used the examples and assignments in the book to build and modify websites, and I quickly took what I was learning and started building my designs.\r\n\r\nThis happened several months before I was ready to design the fansite, so I used this knowledge on small personal projects and client work. I was building a lot of confidence with each new project, and soon I was comfortably writing code and making web sites with HTML5 and CSS. The timing was incredible, because when I was ready to start the design phase of this project, I could focus on how to write my code for WordPress; not just how to write the code.\r\n\r\nGraduate school didnt teach me everything I need to know about web design. It introduced me to new ideas and taught me to be a life-long learner. This has been one of the most positive experiences of my entire life, and to top it all off, I have a masters degree to show for it. I am so grateful for the opportunity this program gave me to realize my potential in this field, and for encouraging me to do what I love.', 'Reflection Paper: Conclusion', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'reflection-paper-project-conclusion', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1123', 0, 'post', '', 0),
