(1498, 1, '2014-09-21 06:16:17', '2014-09-21 13:16:17', 'When WordPress started as a blogging platform 10 years ago, I doubt anyone guessed it would evolve into a full blown content management system. And there is no shortage of beautiful and affordable WordPress themes to choose from, either. The selection on a marketplace like <a href="http://themeforest.net/">Themeforest </a>alone is staggering and impressive. Ive had a chance, however, to see the backend of some of those themes, and my reaction to their theme options is disappointment.\r\n\r\nIve had several clients ask me to build websites using premium themes, and Im happy to do so. I love helping new and growing businesses and this is usually an affordable option for someone who needs a web presence. But when the theme is installed and I begin to sort out what can be achieved in the theme options versus what will require a child theme, I sometimes regret my decision.\r\n\r\nThis almost always happens the first time I work with a premium theme. I am an experienced WordPress user, and even I find some theme options to be so complex, I actually get nervous about how Ill explain them to the client. And in a few situations Ive spent a couple of hours making adjustments with theme options, only to install a child theme and have every theme option be reset to their default.\r\n\r\nWhich brings me to another point; while premium themes are a lovely and affordable option, I have yet to use one on a site where it met all of the clients needs. Despite options for layout, typography, sliders, and moving parts galore, I still need to install a child theme for added customizations. And while pretty much every site is responsive, they can hardly be well optimized for mobile devices with copious amounts of http requests and multiple database queries.\r\n\r\nIm also not afraid to admit that Im occasionally intimidated by some of the designs I see in a place like Themeforest. I love great design, so nothing has been more disappointing than the realization that design is hard! Im a pretty good front end developer, but Ive had to work harder at becoming a good designer more than learning HTML, CSS, and WordPress combined. What was a custom website three or four years ago now costs $58, and Ive wondered if, as a freelancer, I can possibly compete or stay in business at all.\r\n\r\nBottom line: I believe people still need to deal with people. If Im overwhelmed by a set of theme options, clients arent going to feel much better. And while many themes come with complex support systems, it might be a good idea to step back and evaluate why this level of support is necessary. Is it purely a numbers game, or is it that the functionality being built into premium themes isnt appropriate for an audience only willing to spend a few dollars on a website? I dont know, Im just asking.\r\n\r\nNow that Ive been exposed to several premium themes, Ive stopped worrying about my job and Ive adapted my business accordingly. I still believe premium themes are a good value, but inexpensive should not mean cheap. Clients will still need to pay for the time it takes to properly implement these themes, and be prepared for the learning curve to effectively use them.', 'Choose Your Premium WordPress Theme Wisely', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'choose-your-premium-wordpress-theme-wisely', '', '', '2014-10-19 12:56:16', '2014-10-19 19:56:16', '', 0, 'http://angelajholden.com/?p=1498', 0, 'post', '', 2),
